{"title":"How to create a serverless full static website","excerpt":"","content":"<p><img src=\"http://localhost:3030/uploads/whoobe-j4qmm.webp\" width=\"359\" style=\"cursor: nesw-resize;\">As a developer sometimes I need to publish websites for demo purposes, so I really need an easy solution that has the following goals:</p><ul><li>fast design</li><li>creative design tools</li><li>fast deployment</li><li>serverless</li></ul><p><br></p><p>I was working on some projects using a custom CMS based on Feathersjs in order to have a real headless CMS, easy to setup, maintain and open to development.</p><p><br></p><p>And what about coding? Yes whatever you use as frontend (Vue, Nuxt, React, Angular, etc.) you need by the way to code your HTML, CSS and some JS. I know, sometimes developers coding the HTML markup and relative CSS is a boring process, even using templates that you created before for some other project.</p><p><br></p><p>I wanted something different that could improve my creative process experience with something that was WYSIWYG and that could make the markup job for me.</p><p><br></p><p>I created Whoobe a frontend application based on blocks design, that works as a developer tool. I can create pages, templates, components, widgets, sliders, flipcards, modal, popups and more without coding a single line of HTML and CSS. Yes.</p><p>Give it a try. It's open source and free.</p><p><br></p><h3><strong>Serverless or not serverless?</strong></h3><p><br></p><p>What means serverless? A website that can be hosted on any webserver, full static, that doesn't require any API or any other server or database to connect to.</p><p>I decided to go with NuxtJS because is the best that I know and also because Whoobe is developed using VueJS so I could reuse the same components with no problems.</p><p><br></p><p>With whoobe you can decide to go full static serverless or if you need a production deployment you can still connect to it. It's your choice depending on a single project.</p><p><br></p><h3><strong>Going servless full static</strong></h3><p><br></p><p>With Whoobe Site Generator (NuxtJS) when you generate with static mode, during the generation performs the following:</p><ul><li>generate the routes</li><li>generate the static pages</li><li>generate the dynamic routes based on slugs (you can customize) payload included</li><li>if you are using local media assets it will copy the CMS&nbsp;<strong>./public/uploads</strong>&nbsp;folder to NuxtJS&nbsp;<strong>./static/uploads</strong></li></ul><p><br></p><p>At the end of the generation process you will have your&nbsp;<strong>./dist</strong>&nbsp;folder with your static website.</p><p><br></p><p>Just deploy the ./dist folder without any build or generate command and your website is ready to be published.</p><p><br></p><h3><strong>Updating pages and content</strong></h3><p><br></p><p>When you need to update any content (page, media, etc) using MOKAStudio it will automatically update your CMS data.</p><p>Then you can run a new generate command, commit your changes and your site will be updated automatically.</p><p><br></p><h3><strong>Pros of serverless</strong></h3><p><br></p><p>The main benefits are:</p><ul><li>working in local environment (development) to create, change, update any content</li><li>no server is needed</li><li>no extra cost for expensive infrastructure (AWS, Google Cloud, Azure, etc.)</li><li>no server maintenance or update</li><li>no database backup</li><li>fastest deployment time</li><li>limit downtime risks due to server bottlenecks</li><li>fast response</li><li>secure by the core since is just HTML, CSS and JS</li><li>easy portability and backup (using repos)</li><li>no passwords, permissions settings using a local environemnt</li></ul><p><br></p><p><br></p><h3><strong>Cons of serverless</strong></h3><p>When you have a website that has many updates, or even many editors, publishers you may need a production Whoobe CMS deployment</p><p><br></p><ul><li>frequent updates requires a new generate command with NuxtJS</li></ul>","slug":"how-to-create-a-serverless-full-static-website","homepage":false,"menu":false,"random_image":false,"list_exclude":false,"parent":null,"tags":null,"image_title":null,"component":"Cw24SkxqblO46tGZ","user":null,"lang":"","template_id":"Cw24SkxqblO46tGZ","seo_title":"A simple blog article","seo_description":"A blog article created with whoobe","blocks":{"id":42,"name":"Loop Template","description":"A new Moka component","json":{"id":"moka-1qfsv","css":" bg-white ","image":null,"tag":"document","blocks":[{"css":{"css":" w-full h-1/5 p-6 items-center bg-gray-200 shadow-lg bg-opacity-100 bg-cover bg-right bg-no-repeat bg-opacity-100 bg-cover bg-right bg-no-repeat ","container":"grid md:grid-rows-1 md:grid-cols-5 grid-cols-1"},"loop":false,"blocks":[{"css":{"css":" items-center","container":"flex flex-col md:col-span-1"},"loop":false,"blocks":[{"css":" p-4 ","style":"","label":"Image","content":"","icon":"insert_photo","type":"image","tag":"element","link":"/","id":"moka-ubdku","image":{"name":"whoobe-logo-2-colors.svg","caption":"whoobe-logo-2-colors.svg","alternativeText":"whoobe-logo-2-colors.svg","provider":"local","related":[],"width":0,"height":0,"size":8489,"url":"/uploads/whoobe-logo-2-colors.svg","ext":".svg","mime":"image/svg+xml","formats":null,"_id":"UiqBWs4rToxbPdfC","createdAt":"2021-03-24T16:41:33.809Z","updatedAt":"2021-03-24T16:41:33.809Z"},"element":"img","gsap":{"animation":"","ease":"","duration":0,"delay":0}}],"semantic":"","style":"","label":"Flexbox","content":"","icon":"highlight_alt","rows":[],"type":"flex","tag":"container","link":"","id":"moka-fyg7c","image":null,"element":"div"},{"css":{"css":"","container":"flex flex-col md:col-span-4"},"loop":false,"blocks":[{"items":[{"link":"#","label":"Link","title":"menu item","icon":"","icon_tag":"","image":"","items":[],"blocks":[]}],"css":{"css":" items-center justify-around  text-xl","items":"right-0 text-white","align":"justify-start","submen